  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 9.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Appointed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "of refuge or resort.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Our version has followed the LXX. and Vulgate here. Greek, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "unawares",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "in error",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "inadvertently",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as above. Matthew Henry's note on the cities of refuge is worthy of remark. He says, \"I delight not in quibbling on names, yet am willing to take notice of these.\" Thus Kedesh, he reminds us, is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "holy.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Shechem, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "a shoulder",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", reminding us of Him upon whose shoulder the government was to be. Hebron is fellowship, recalling the fellowship we have in Christ. Bezer is a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "fortification",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", reminding us of God our stronghold (later criticism, however, gives another derivation to this unusual word, which in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 22:24, 25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", means the ore of a precious metal), Ramoth is height or exaltation, and to such exaltation we are called in Jesus Christ. Lastly, Golan is exultation, so says Matthew Henry, deriving it from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "גִיל",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "גוּל",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But Gesenius derives it with equal probability from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "גלה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"to make bare,\" hence to lead into captivity. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Joshua 20:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
